#Text=Gloriana
#Text=Willow Shaw , the little fenced wood where the hop-poles are stacked like Indian wigwams , had been given to Dan and Una for their very own kingdom when they were quite small .
#Text=As they grew older , they contrived to keep it most particularly private .

#Text=Even Phillips , the gardener , told them every time that he came in to take a hop-pole for his beans , and old Hobden would no more have thought of setting his rabbit-wires there without leave , given fresh each spring , than he would have torn down the calico and marking ink notice on the big willow which said : ‘ Grown-ups not allowed in the Kingdom unless brought . ’
#Text=Now you can understand their indignation when , one blowy July afternoon , as they were going up for a potato-roast , they saw somebody moving among the trees .
#Text=They hurled themselves over the gate , dropping half the potatoes , and while they were picking them up Puck came out of a wigwam .
#Text=‘ Oh , it ’s you , is it ? ’ said Una .
#Text=‘ We thought it was people . ’
#Text=‘ I saw you were angry -- from your legs , ’ he answered with a grin .
#Text=‘ Well , it ’s our own Kingdom -- not counting you , of course . ’
#Text=‘ That ’s rather why I came .
#Text=A lady here wants to see you . ’
#Text=‘ What about ? ’ said Dan cautiously .
#Text=‘ Oh , just Kingdoms and things .
#Text=She knows about Kingdoms . ’
#Text=There was a lady near the fence dressed in a long dark cloak that hid everything except her high red-heeled shoes .
#Text=Her face was half covered by a black silk fringed mask , without goggles .
#Text=And yet she did not look in the least as if she motored .
#Text=Puck led them up to her and bowed solemnly .
#Text=Una made the best dancing-lesson curtsy she could remember .
#Text=The lady answered with a long , deep , slow , billowy one .
#Text=‘ Since it seems that you are a Queen of this Kingdom , ’ she said , ‘ I can do no less than acknowledge your sovereignty . ’
#Text=She turned sharply on staring Dan .
#Text=‘ What ’s in your head , lad ?
#Text=Manners ? ’
#Text=‘ I was thinking how wonderfully you did that curtsy , ’ he answered .
#Text=She laughed a rather shrill laugh .
#Text=‘ You ’re a courtier already .
#Text=Do you know anything of dances , wench -- or Queen , must I say ? ’
#Text=‘ I ’ve had some lessons , but I ca n’t really dance a bit , ’ said Una .
#Text=‘ You should learn , then . ’
#Text=The lady moved forward as though she would teach her at once .
#Text=‘ It gives a woman alone among men or her enemies time to think how she shall win or -- lose .
#Text=A woman can only work in man ’s play-time .
#Text=Heigho ! ’
#Text=She sat down on the bank .
#Text=Old Middenboro , the lawn-mower pony , stumped across the paddock and hung his sorrowful head over the fence .
#Text=‘ A pleasant Kingdom , ’ said the lady , looking round .
#Text=‘ Well enclosed .
#Text=And how does your Majesty govern it ?
#Text=Who is your Minister ? ’
#Text=Una did not quite understand .
#Text=‘ We do n’t play that , ’ she said .
#Text=‘ Play ? ’
#Text=The lady threw up her hands and laughed .
#Text=‘ We have it for our own , together , ’ Dan explained .
#Text=‘ And d’you never quarrel , young Burleigh ? ’
#Text=‘ Sometimes , but then we do n’t tell . ’
#Text=The lady nodded .
#Text=‘ I ’ve no brats of my own , but I understand keeping a secret between Queens and their Ministers .
#Text=Ay de mi !
#Text=But with no disrespect to present majesty , methinks your realm ’ small , and therefore likely to be coveted by man and beast .
#Text=For Is example’ -- she pointed to Middenboro -- ‘yonder old horse , with the face of a Spanish friar -- does he never break in ? ’
#Text=‘ He ca n’t .
#Text=Old Hobden stops all our gaps for us , ’ said Una , ‘ and we let Hobden catch rabbits in the Shaw . ’
#Text=The lady laughed like a man .
#Text=‘ I see !
#Text=Hobden catches conies -- rabbits -- for himself , and guards your defences for you .
#Text=Does he make a profit out of his coney-catching ? ’
#Text=‘ We never ask , ’ said Una .
#Text=‘ Hobden ’s a particular friend of ours . ’
#Text=‘ Hoity-toity ! ’ the lady began angrily .
#Text=Then she laughed .
#Text=‘ But I forget .
#Text=It is your Kingdom .
#Text=I knew a maid once that had a larger one than this to defend , and so long as her men kept the fences stopped , she asked ‘ em no questions either . ’
#Text=‘ Was she trying to grow flowers ? ’ said Una .
#Text=‘ No , trees -- perdurable trees .
#Text=Her flowers all withered . ’
#Text=The lady leaned her head on her hand .
#Text=‘ They do if you do n’t look after them .
#Text=We ’ve got a few .
#Text=Would you like to see ?
#Text=I ’ll fetch you some . ’
#Text=Una ran off to the rank grass in the shade behind the wigwam , and came back with a handful of red flowers .
#Text=‘ Are n’t they pretty ? ’ she said .
#Text=‘ They ’re Virginia stock . ’
#Text=‘ Virginia ? ’ said the lady , and lifted them to the fringe of her mask .
#Text=‘ Yes .
#Text=They come from Virginia .
#Text=Did your maid ever plant any ? ’
#Text=‘ Not herself -- but her men adventured all over the earth to pluck or to plant flowers for her crown .
#Text=They judged her worthy of them . ’
#Text=‘ And was she ? ’ said Dan cheerfully .
#Text=‘ Quien sabe ? [ who knows ? ]
#Text=But at least , while her men toiled abroad she toiled in England , that they might find a safe home to come back to . ’
#Text=‘ And what was she called ? ’
#Text=‘ Gloriana -- Belphoebe -- Elizabeth of England . ’
#Text=Her voice changed at each word .
#Text=‘ You mean Queen Bess ? ’
#Text=The lady bowed her head a little towards Dan .
#Text=‘ You name her lightly enough , young Burleigh .
#Text=What might you know of her ? ’ said she .
#Text=‘ Well , I -- I ’ve seen the little green shoes she left at Brickwall House -- down the road , you know .
#Text=They ’re in a glass case -- awfully tiny things . ’
#Text=‘ Oh , Burleigh , Burleigh ! ’ she laughed .
#Text=‘ You are a courtier too soon . ’
